If you import something nonlocal, Node will look for a matching directory inside the node_modules folder in current directory.
If it doesn't find it there, it will go up to the parent directory and try again.
It keeps going up until it reaches the root of your filesystem.

It's important to note that it doesn't consult package.json at all when doing this -- not for the importer or the imported package.

There are two kinds of packages it looks for:
* regular packages: example.
* modules that are in organizations: @example/example

Packages in an organization always begin with @.
When node sees that, it knows the real module name is @example/example, not just @example.
This is how it knows where to start looking for code.

Notice even for these node_modules you still don't need package.json!